117· Ennius: Q. Ennius (b. 239 ac. at Rudiae in Calabria, d. 169) was “in letters what Scipio was in action, the most vital representa· tive of his epoeh. It was to him, not to Naeviusor Plautus, that the Romans lookcd as the father ol their literature.” Of hiswritings only fragments remain. The most important was the Annales, the first great Latin epic in hexameter verse, celebrating the achievements oi the Roman people from Aeneas down to the poet’s own time. Lucr. looked to Ennius as his master in verse, aud shows in many passages traces of his influence. Vergil likewise and others found in Ennius, it not a model, at least a poet oi whom many verses could be with fitness transferred and imitated. Ennius was a Pythagoream He boasted, it is said, that the soul ol Homer, having passed through many bodies, among which in particular was that of a peacoclr, had come into his own.
